04298nam a22007335i 9781442684980DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222008onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426849807 a10.3138/97814426849802doi  a(DE-B1597)626543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHQ1236.5.C2bS49 2007 7aLAW0600002bisacsh04a342.710291 aSharpe, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Persons Case :bThe Origins and Legacy of the Fight for Legal Personhood /cPatricia I. McMahon, Robert J. Sharpe. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOsgoode Society for Canadian Legal History0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn 18 October 1929, John Sankey, England's reform-minded Lord Chancellor, ruled in the Persons case that women were eligible for appointment to Canada's Senate. Initiated by Edmonton judge Emily Murphy and four other activist women, the Persons case challenged the exclusion of women from Canada's upper house and the idea that the meaning of the constitution could not change with time. The Persons Case considers the case in its political and social context and examines the lives of the key players: Emily Murphy, Nellie McClung, and the other members of the "famous five," the politicians who opposed the appointment of women, the lawyers who argued the case, and the judges who decided it. Robert J. Sharpe and Patricia I. McMahon examine the Persons case as a pivotal moment in the struggle for women's rights and as one of the most important constitutional decisions in Canadian history. Lord Sankey's decision overruled the Supreme Court of Canada's judgment that the courts could not depart from the original intent of the framers of Canada's constitution in 1867. Describing the constitution as a "living tree," the decision led to a reassessment of the nature of the constitution itself. After the Persons case, it could no longer be viewed as fixed and unalterable, but had to be treated as a document that, in the words of Sankey, was in "a continuous process of evolution." The Persons Case is a comprehensive study of this important event, examining the case itself, the ruling of the Privy Council, and the profound affect that it had on women's rights and the constitutional history of Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aPersons (Law)zCanadaxHistory. 0aPolitical rightszCanadaxHistory. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen's rightszCanadaxHistory. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh1 aMcMahon, Patricia I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcMurtry, R. Roy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268498040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442684980423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442684980/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK